#1652
The Tempest's Heart~
@@RHere at the center of the second circle's storm the winds reach their
@@Rmaximum fury, strong enough to lift stone and tear the ground. The sky
@@Ris a vortex of bruised purple and deep crimson, shot through with
@@Rlightning that never quite strikes. Famous lovers circle through this
@@Rcenter in pairs, still together in their punishment as they were in
@@Rlife, which would be touching if they were not screaming. The irony
@@Rof being inseparable from the one whose love condemned you is not lost
@@Ron any of them. The storm speaks here in fragments of the love poetry
@@Rthe damned once composed, recited back at them in a register just below
@@Rcomfort and just above mockery. The wind is sharp enough to draw blood.
@@RYou will want to leave. You will have some difficulty doing so.
